Congressional Cosponsorship Networks¶

Holden Huntzinger -- 1/17/23

The code snippets below represent small pieces of a larger solo data mining project. You can find the rest of that project, including relevant data files and Python scripts as well as a conference-style poster and a formal written report, at https://github.com/hhuntz/congressional_networks.

The code below pulls in CSVs from the 'data' folder there. Those come from additional sources (Congress.gov and Propublica, full citations on Github) as well as the compile_data.py script I wrote to turn bill-level data into edges between MOCs.

Summary¶

  • I cast sponsorship information from 325,000 bills across 20 Congressional sessions 1973 - 2021 as a network. MOCs became nodes and the weights of their edges represented the frequency of cosponsorships.
  • Democrats were more likely to cosponsor bills across party lines; a T-test demonstrates this difference as statistically significant.
  • More 'legislatively central' Republicans (by pagerank, a form of eigenvector centrality) tend to cosponsor within their party while more central Democrats engage in more cross-party cosponsorship. A 2-way ANOVA shows the statistical significance of this relationship.
  • I know how to make cool interactive graphs.

    Defining Terms¶

    Pagerank is a variation of eigenvector centrality originally used by Google to rank search results by counting an incoming link as a vote of support and weighting incoming links based on the score of the linking page; applied to the network of members of Congress, this is one rough proxy for measuring the legislative importance of a member. Members with more cosponsorship connections and whose connections have more connections are very central and so, I posit, legislatively important.

    Bipartisan cosponsorship score measures how often a member of Congress has sponsored bills alongside members outside of their own political party relative to how many total cosponsorship relationships they have.

    # interactive plot
# bipart score by pagerank centrality

repubs = alt.Chart(df[df.party == 'Republican']).mark_point(color = 'red', opacity = 0.1).encode(
    x = alt.X('bipartisan_cosponsorship_score', title = 'Bipartisan Cosponsorship'),
    y = alt.Y('pagerank', title = 'Pagerank Centrality'),
    tooltip = ['first_name', 'last_name', 'state', 'district']
).properties(title = "Bipartisanship and Centrality by Party")

dems = alt.Chart(df[df.party == 'Democrat']).mark_circle(color = 'blue', opacity = 0.1).encode(
    x = alt.X('bipartisan_cosponsorship_score'),
    y = alt.Y('pagerank'),
    tooltip = ['first_name', 'last_name', 'state', 'district']
)

dem_line = dems.transform_regression('bipartisan_cosponsorship_score', 'pagerank').mark_line(color = 'blue')

repub_line = repubs.transform_regression('bipartisan_cosponsorship_score', 'pagerank').mark_line(color = 'red')

dems.interactive() + repubs.interactive() + dem_line + repub_line

    Hypothesis Testing¶

    T-test¶

    Is the difference between Republican and Democrat bipartisan cosponsorship scores statistically significant?

    In [83]:
    ttest_ind(df[df.party == 'Democrat'].bipartisan_cosponsorship_score, 
          df[df.party == 'Republican'].bipartisan_cosponsorship_score)
    Out[83]:
    Ttest_indResult(statistic=34.12611404107078, pvalue=8.773133824228066e-210)

    The p-value here is miniscule, as expected -- with this many observations, the visual difference was bound to be significant.

    ANOVA¶

    Is the relationship between bipartisan cosponsorship and pagerank similarly significant? Is the difference by party between the 2 OLS regression lines significant?

    In [108]:
    # log pagerank b/c 2-way ANOVA assumes normally distributed dependant variable
df['log_pagerank'] = np.log(df.pagerank)

# fit linear model
lm = smf.ols("log_pagerank ~ bipartisan_cosponsorship_score + bipartisan_cosponsorship_score:C(party)", data = df).fit()

# get ANOVA stats
table = sm.stats.anova_lm(lm, typ = 2)
table

    Both p-values are very small, so we now know that not only is the relationship between bipartisan cosponsorship score and pagerank centrality significant (if quite weak), but the difference between parties is too.
